his theme not only through close readings of Schelling's texts, but also by bringing them into dialogue with thinkers as diverse as Deleuze, Nietzsche, Melville, Musil, and many others. The book also features the first appearance in English translation of Schelling's famous letter to Eschenmayer regarding the Freedom essay.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aAesthetics. 0aPhilosophy of nature. 0aThought and thinking. 4aPhilosophy : German Idealism. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy of Religion. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aLauer, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWirth, Jason M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2015z978311149061840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143845680540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438456805423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438456805/original  a978-3-11-149061-8  SUNY Press eBook Package 2015b2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles